VII. PREVENTION PROGRAM

The Commission?s accidental release prevention program is part of the agencies overall Safety and Health Program and involves a unified approach that integrates technologies, procedures and management practices to ensure our workers and the public a safe environment. The RMP requirements are essentially an expansion of the OSHA Process Safety requirement and the Employee and Community Right-To-Know Programs that have been in existence for a number of years.

Hazardous material has always been recognized as a unique hazard for our employees and the public. Therefore, we have made every possible effort to ensure the proper and safe use of all hazardous materials. WSSC?s Hazardous Material Safety Program includes: 
- The availability of personal protective equipment; 
- Obtaining and use of Material Safety Data Sheets (MSDS); 
- Designing facilities for safety and accident prevention; 
- Training and educating employees on chemical systems and processes; 
- Planning and practicing for emergency situations; 
- Requiring consultants and contractors to abide by established safety practices; 
- Sharing of information with employees, contractor and consultants; 
- Conducting periodic inspections and audits reviews of chemical process systems; 
- Formulating policies and procedures for an effective chemical handling process.

Additionally, all Commission facilities are designed and built in conformance with the industries recognized codes, such as:
- National Electrical Code;
- American Society of Mechanical Engineers;
- American National Standards Institute;
- ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Codes;
- BOCA Codes;
- American Society of Heating, Refrigeration and Air Conditioning Engineers;
- American Water Works Association

A review of the hazards associated with the chlorine facility process and procedure is performed annually.

